= How does Verified Boot work? =
The verification can be based on digests or digital signatures (i.e., signed digests). Only components with expected digests or those signed with a private key trusted by the device are loaded and executed. Otherwise, the device can refuse to boot.

Lower stage (such as firmware) loads and hands over control to the next element in a boot chain (such as bootloader).  In general, every stage verifies the digital signature of the next one.

The stages look approximately as follows (simplified):

<code>hardware root of trust</code> → <code>firmware</code> → <code>bootloader</code> → <code>kernel</code> → <code>kernel modules</code> → <code>initrd</code> → <code>init</code>

Or specifically on some Linux desktop distributions:

<code>hardware root of trust</code> → <code>firmware</code> → <code>shim</code> -> <code>grub</code> <code>bootloader</code> → <code>Linux kernel</code> → <code>kernel modules</code> → <code>initrd</code> → <code>systemd</code> <code>init</code> and <code>userland</code>

Should the verification fail at any stage, the boot process is aborted.

There is no technical requirement for each stage to be signed with the same key. Each stage can have a dedicated key or even key management system.

= Applicability of Verified Boot =

== What are the advantages of verified boot? ==
Thanks to the integrity check, unauthorized malware can be eliminated after a reboot (if the device is capable of reverting to a clean backup image) or the device won't boot.

Conceptually, this improves security because the user runs only applications with a valid digital signature. This excludes third-party unauthorized malware which would have to be signed with a valid key while infecting the system to circumvent the checks (possible if a vendor key is leaked or the system is under a targeted attack that got a hold of a key at an earlier stage).

== What are the limitations of verified boot? ==
Doesn't protect the system from "authorized" malware. For example, the pre-installed Google Play Services on Google Android or a malicious application that successfully passed all appstore checks. See [[Mobile_Phone_Security#Espionage_Data_Harvesting|massive espionage data harvesting on Google Android]]. Verified boot is a security technology that conceptually cannot stop [[malware]] that is built into an operating system by its producer. This does not take away from its useful potential as a security improvement for users.

== Who uses verified boot? ==
At the time of writing, there was no Freedom Software Linux desktop distribution that implemented full verified boot which means a full chain of verification starting form the hardware root of trust up to all pre-installed applications that come with the Linux distribution. Only kernel module verification is supported. The verified boot for initrd and beyond is not yet implemented. ([[Verified_Boot#Other_Distributions_implementing_Verified_Boot|Other Distributions implementing Verified Boot
]])

By comparison, for example Android and iOS supports full verified boot.

== What are the dangers of verified boot? ==
The main risks are mistreatment of users, user software freedom restrictions, taking power away from users and handing it over to operating system and application developers.

As verified boot is currently implemented, for the vast supermajority of users the key is controlled by the operating system vendor. Users enrolling their own keys in the hardware key store or at any later stage of the boot process is often literally impossible <ref>
Many Android devices come with locked bootloaders. Many Android phones could not have been modded by the modding community because no way to break the verified boot chain and gain full read/write access to their own devices could be found.
</ref>, undocumented, not well supported, and even discouraged.

Many user-freedom restrictions are enforced using verified boot, locked bootloaders and non-root enforcement. This includes [[Mobile_Operating_System_Comparison#Android_Anti-Features|Android Anti-Features]], prevention of replacing the stock operating system on mobile devices and [[Miscellaneous_Threats_to_User_Freedom#mobile_devices_restrictions|many other mobile devices restrictions]].

== When the verification is over? ==

Potential misconception:

<blockquote>
Verified boot makes sure that the boot process has not been tampered with, and then from that point on its job is done.
</blockquote>

Quote https://source.android.com/docs/security/features/verifiedboot/verified-boot

<blockquote>
verification is a continuous process happening as data is loaded into memory
</blockquote>

This means if malware manages to modify the <code>/usr/bin/mv</code> program despite immutability, then <code>dm-verity</code> would notice this the next time the user or system is attempting to execute that command.

