==== Raspberry Pi RPi Based ====

Raspberry Pi 4 and Raspberry Pi 5 support non-UEFI secure boot.

They allow user- or OEM-provided signing key fusing.

This is significantly easier to use than Intel Boot Guard or AMD PSP, as it does not require special permission from the ODM.

Raspberry Pi 4 or 5 appears to be the most straightforward path to achieving verified boot of a Linux kernel.

Boot chain: Raspberry Pi hardware -> Raspberry Pi bootloader -> Linux. This forms a fully protected boot chain, executing only signed code.

