= Protecting the Kernel Command Line =
Draft.

Features:

* allow customization of kernel command line at boot time
* protect the kernel command line against evil maid attacks

The kernel command line needs to be protected to avoid an attacker with physical access to the device from using [[Recovery#Recovery_Mode|Linux Recovery Mode]] as well as [[Recovery#Emergency_Recovery_Console|Emergency Recovery Console]] (by an initramfs-generator such as [[dracut]] or initramfs-tools).

As described in blog post [https://insinuator.net/2025/07/insecure-boot-injecting-initramfs-from-a-debug-shell/ Insecure Boot: Injecting initramfs from a debug shell] an attacker with physical access can compromise the initramfs. The same goes for Linux recovery mode.

A potential solution could be using [[Full_Disk_Encryption#encrypted_boot|encrypted <code>/boot</code> partition]]:

# [[Sovereign Boot]]: Makes sure that only bootloaders can be started which are signed by keys accepted by the user.
# [[Dev/boot#GRUB_Full_Disk_Encryption|GRUB <u>F</u>ull <u>D</u>isk <u>E</u>ncryption (FDE)]]: GRUB would show a [[Grub#EFI_-_GRUB_Bootloader_Disk_Decryption_Password_Prompt|EFI - GRUB Bootloader Disk Decryption Password Prompt]].
# Thanks to GRUB FDE, kernel command line changes are only possible after providing full disk encryption password.

In result, the kernel command line would be protected.

The advantage of this solution would be that it is antagonistic about components such as kernel, initramfs generator, unified kernel image (UKI) and so forth.

For now, [https://forums.kicksecure.com/t/installing-fde-luks-with-detached-luks-header-option/907/2 GRUB FDE has been deemed unsuitable due to issues]: [[Full_Disk_Encryption#encrypted_boot|encrypted <code>/boot</code> partition]]

These issues may or may not be unfixable due to [[Dev/boot#GRUB_Slow_Upstream|GRUB Slow Upstream]]. Software forking GRUB is not an option at this time due to [[Dev/maintainability|maintainability]] concerns.

What happens in case an evil maid removes the hard drive, replaces the bootloader with a malicious GRUB version designed to steal the password or compromise the system? The evil maid will lack access to the vendor or user key used to sign the bootloader. Hence, [[Sovereign Boot]] will refuse to boot it.

If using unencrypted boot, using a signed UKI (a unified kernel image that contains a kernel image combined with an initramfs) - which is the approach by systemd-boot - might also work. But how support the feature of allow kernel parameter edits as well as to protect the kernel command line in this case?

TODO: Any answers here? https://0pointer.net/blog/fitting-everything-together.html

forum discussion: https://forums.kicksecure.com/t/protecting-the-kernel-command-line/1251

